Chapter 3 of Data Camp - Intro to Time Series Analsys

Scatterplots

Log returns

apply diff(log(stock_price)) to each stock, then bind them with cbind() and plot.

Log Returns or continuously compounded returns are a commonly used value in financial time series analysis. They are to log of gross returns.

data("EuStockMarkets")

plot(EuStockMarkets)

# Use this code to convert prices to returns
returns <- EuStockMarkets[-1,] / EuStockMarkets[-1860,] - 1

# Convert returns to ts
returns <- ts(returns, start = c(1991, 130), frequency = 260)

# Plot returns
plot(returns)

# Use this code to convert prices to log returns
logreturns <- diff(log(EuStockMarkets))

# Plot logreturns
plot(logreturns)

Calculating column stats

See the colMeans(), colSum(), etc or the dot versions, .colMeans() for calculating column or row statistics on a dataset.

Covariance

cov() is used to calculate the covariance between to datasets which are related over time. Positive covariance implies a positive relationship. Covariance measures teh strength of the linear relationship between matched pairs of variables.

covariance are dependant on the size of the values. So it’s hard to interpret the value.

Correlations

  • Standardized version of covariance between -1 and 1.
  • +1 is perfect positive linear relationship
  • -1 is perfect negative linear relationship
    • is no linear relationship

cor() is used to calculate the correlation. This is the covariance divided by the product of the sd of the 2 inputs. e.g. cov(stock_a, stock_b) / (sd(stock_a) * sd(stock_b)).

cor() and cov() can be used on 2 time series or on a matrix with multiple colums to compare.

DAX_logreturns <- ts(diff(log(EuStockMarkets[,'DAX'])), start=c(1991, 131), frequency=260)
FTSE_logreturns <- ts(diff(log(EuStockMarkets[,'FTSE'])), start=c(1991, 131), frequency=260)

cov(DAX_logreturns, FTSE_logreturns)
## [1] 5.241794e-05

Autocorrelation

A means to determine how a value relates to a previous value.

Autocorelation at lag 1 is comparing current value to the previous, lag=2 todays prior.

The AutoCorrelation Function (ACF)

The acf() function calculates the Autocorrelation for a series based on the indicated lag. It will also plot the autocorrelation(s) if plot=TRUE is set. If no lag is specified, it will calculate 0 - 10.

NOTE: acf calculates the correlation using 1/n, which is preferable for time series, wherase the cor() function uses 1/n-1. This means that the acf() value is close but off by a factor of n-1/n.

x = ts(arima.sim(model=list(order=c(0,0,0)), n=150),
        start=1, frequency=1)

x0 = x[-1]
x1 = x[-150]

head(cbind(x0, x1))
##              x0         x1
## [1,]  0.2654861  0.3786456
## [2,] -0.1756523  0.2654861
## [3,] -0.2358109 -0.1756523
## [4,]  0.6100009 -0.2358109
## [5,] -0.1463352  0.6100009
## [6,]  0.5508207 -0.1463352
plot(x0, x1)

cor(x0, x1)
## [1] -0.01961494
acf(x, lag.max = 1, plot=FALSE)
## 
## Autocorrelations of series 'x', by lag
## 
##     0     1 
##  1.00 -0.02
cor(x0, x1) * (149 / 150)
## [1] -0.01948417
